<br>
Secondly, as far as dividing up the electoral votes in individual states based on the number of votes they get, this has been tried.  The decision was made to move away from it because in close elections there would be no candidate that made the required number of electoral votes.  There are, I believe, two states that still do it this way... vermont and hawaii (could be wrong, but I know its a west coast state and a new england one).<br>
<br>
Third, the electoral system really only gives the illusion of giving the smaller states more power.  It is still the big states that are needed to win the presidency.  Further, this illusion of power in reality is actually removing the power from the people.  As Mills said, the people that vote for the losing candidate get their vote thrown out.  I believe this is completely wrong (see IRV debates on equal voting hehe).  This country needs its power base to be closer to the people not farther away.  Eliminating the electoral college is one of the most obviouse ways to do that.<br>
<br>
It is possible that there is some way to reform the electoral college and make it work better.  Something along the lines of changing the total electoral votes required to become president coincident with reverting to giving votes out based on number of votes in the home state.  This would help to maintain the balance of power among the states that was fought so hard for in the creation of this country.  <br>
<br>
Here is a thought on this, and it is just a thought.  What about going with a mixed system.  Take the electoral votes that represent each states senators and give them out in the same way they do now.  While taking the remaining votes and tabulating the figures nationwide.  This would give smaller parties a better opportunity to get electoral votes as they would be able to pool their votes across the nation, while still maintaining the power balance of the big states (the reason they have more electoral votes now is because they have much larger populations).  Its just a thought, let me know what you think.<br>
<br>
Also, here's another thought.  Big states will hate it, but too bad.  What if we changed the way electoral votes were distributed to reflect the number of people that voted instead of the number of people that lived in a particular state.  For example (totally random figures) if WA had 3 million voters and population of 5 million and OR had 4 million voters and a population 4.5 million in the current set up WA would get more electoral votes, where as if we changed it to what I am thinking OR would get more electoral votes.  I haven't thought much about it, but off the top of my head it seems like an excellent way to encourage voter turn out which equates to more power for more people (rather than more power for fewer people).  I wuld think you would have to do it on the following elections, but maybe you could do it on the current elections (computers can do wonderful things) which would be ideal.  Just thinking.<br>
<br>
Locke<br>
